post_text: Welcome to #ThinkAboutItThursdays! This is where we put on our thinking caps and explore intriguing ideas. Today's thought: What kind of learner are you? Which of your senses, when utilized, promotes the most retention? The great news about the human brain is that it's not picky about the way information is inputted. Some folks learn best from listening, while others benefit from seeing. Still others need something tangible to represent what they're learning. It's not a bad idea to figure out what makes you tick and try implementing things that cater to that particular learning style!

Some folks learn best from listening, while others benefit from seeing. Still others need something tangible to represent what they're learning. It's not a bad idea to figure out what makes you tick and try implementing things that cater to that particular learning style!

post_text: Is your high school student interested in a future in aerospace? Check out this news from the U.S. Department of Education this week!
shared_text:
U.S. Department of Education
August 18 at 9:44 AM ·

Today, the U.S. Department of Education launched CTE Mission: CubeSat, a national challenge to build technical skills for careers in #space and beyond. We invite high schools to bring space missions to students by designing and building #CubeSat prototypes.

To participate, submit a mission proposal online by October 16 — no in-person collaboration or prior experience with CubeSats is required. Curated educational resources are available to teachers and students online, and up to five finalists will each receive $5,000 and additional in-kind prizes. https://www.ctemissioncubesat.com/?utm_source=ED-Facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=launch #CTEMission #CTE #CubeSat

post_text:
We are FLEXIBLE!
Our first grade teacher was recently asked what a typical day looks like for a 1st grader. Her response describes our elementary program perfectly!

"A typical day for a first grader will involve following along the daily lesson plans alongside their guardian that are laid out for each subject online. There is a combination of work to be completed in workbooks along with supplemental online videos and activities. Twice a week, first graders are encouraged to participate in a group lesson with their first-grade teacher, or students can request one-on-one time with their teacher as well. Suggested schedules are provided and time requirements are given, but Sequoia Choice AZDL allows you the flexibility to create the exact schedule that works for your unique family's needs. "

We have a 7 -year safety record of keeping our students safe during virtual learning sessions. All staff has been trained in virtual learning safety precautions. These include:
*Secured meeting URL's
*Use of waiting room feature
*Managing screen and video sharing
*Muting participants upon entry
*Limiting file transfer,
*Disabling private chat
*Allowing only those identified as our students to enter.

Mark Plitzuweit, CEO Edkey, Inc.

post_text: Edkey, Inc.'s CEO Mark Plitzuweit presenting perspective on the "Penny for Ed" legislation last week at the Arizona State Capitol. This legislation (if passed) would place an additional 4/10ths of a sales tax, specifically for education, on the 2020 ballot, and allow voters to decide. K-12 would get 75%, or roughly $325 additional per Arizona public school student. The press conference allocated 2 minutes, but he took 3 minutes to get all of the information in. Long story short - if you spend $100 today, if this legislation gets passed through to the voters and then approved, it would increase that same purchase to $100.40.

AzMerit testing will take place March 29th, 30th, and 31st. All parents should have received information regarding testing from their child's advisor. Attendance is VERY important on these days. Here are some helpful hints to prepare your child for testing:

-Please be positive about the testing opportunity! This is a chance for students to show their best efforts and is not cause for feeling stressed, anxious or nervous.

-Help your student get plenty rest the night before testing.

-Don't forget an excellent breakfast with is filling! You can also pack some snacks,

-Please arrive on time at your testing site.

Let's have an excellent testing session!

post_text:
Don't miss your chance to support students and possibly lower your tax bill.

Make an ECA tax credit donation to Sequoia Charter Schools and change a student's life.

Every dollar goes toward extracurricular activities, and you may choose which school or program you'd like to support. Even better, qualifying taxpayers will receive a dollar-for-dollar credit on their state taxes. The state credit is available to all taxpayers who qualify in the state of Arizona.

Even if you don't live in the district or have a child enrolled in school you can participate, so please share this opportunity with friends and family.

Learn more about ECA and donate online at http://www.sequoiaschools.org/donate today.

Thank you!

The Administrators and Staff of Edkey Inc. and Sequoia Schools

What steps can you follow to be a successful online learner? Take a look at this great article that gives FIVE main steps to being a great online learner.

1) Read your syllabus
2) Plan your weekly study times
3) Log into your courses frequently. The article states three hours a week, but for Sequoia Choice we ask students to spend at least an hour in each course daily.
4) Ask questions!
5) Make connections with fellow students. This may be more difficult for students working from home, but if you are in a lab, get to know others in your classes.

Source: https://onlinelearninginsights.wordpress.com/2012/09/28/five-step-strategy-for-student-success-with-online-learning/

Google Chrome has the most AMAZING extensions to assist students in learning. Since most students use Google Chrome to access their courses, I wanted to share with you some of these great extensions. You can simply search "Google Chrome Store" to add these directly to your browser. Some of my personal favorites are:
-Grammarly (Spell and grammar check for everything you write online.)
-Simple To-Do List (Keep track of everything you have planned for today.
-Easy Bib Tools (Put together works cited pages in a breeze)

What are some of your favorites?

http://edtechteacher.org/1-chrome-extensions-to-learn-this-summer-maximize-efficiency-enhance-student-learning-from-beth-tracy-sockalosky-on-edudemic/
